g to Los Angeles in order to make films "longer than 60 seconds‚Äù. He interested high-powered producer <inline label="actor"><xref id="1340351" title="Scott Rudin" frag="default" reversefrag="3" reversetitle="" reverselink="true" reversetype="none" display="manual" type="none" uriid="447996" href="bio-197.psml" urititle="Rudin, Scott" mediatype="application/vnd.pageseeder.psml+xml" documenttype="bio">Scott Rudin</xref></inline> in his <inline label="film">The Truman Show</inline> (<inline label="year">1998</inline>) script, but Rudin was not willing to gamble on a rookie director, particularly when <inline label="actor"><xref id="1340352" title="Jim Carrey" frag="default" reversefrag="3" reversetitle="" reverselink="true" reversetype="none" display="manual" type="none" uriid="448131" href="bio-105.psml" urititle="Carrey, Jim" mediatype="application/vnd.pageseeder.psml+xml" documenttype="bio">Jim Carrey</xref></inline> came aboard, swelling the budget to about $60 million.</para></fragment></section><section id="wiki" title="Wiki Link"><fragment id="6"><para><link href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Andrew_Niccol&amp;oldid=759454510">https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Andrew_Niccol&amp;oldid=759454510</link></para></fragment></section><section id="image" title="Image"><fragment id="5"/></section></document>